About the Autonum project

2nd January 2019 at 11:14pm
Autonum project

Tiddlywiki (TW) is a cool thing. On its basis, if you wish, you may have an advanced note book, a complete wiki, a scientific or work journal, an address book, a directory, etc. The list can be continued on.

The feature of TW, which makes it extremely attractive, is that it simultaneously satisfies two complementary requirements: autonomy (independence from any external services) and ease of publication (thanks to various interfaces).

TW is not panacea to all problems. TW differs from other wikis used external servers, such as, for example, Mediawiki. In the base version, TW stores and processes all data locally using the built-in Javascript engine. As a result, TW is not intended to work with large volumes of data and, as a rule, is limited to a total of its own built-in volume of several dozens of MB.

Hence, autonomy, ease of publication, a limited data volume - all this is great for preparing and publishing books. But ...

Can books be created using TW?

Typically, wikis do not use the internal numbering system and references of individual text objects, such as tables, formulas, biblographic references, as it accepted for scientific articles and books publishing. TW is not an exception here. This is due to the difference in the ordering of individual articles (sections) between a wiki and a book. While the latter model provides a certain order of articles (sections) in a document (data type - the list), then in the first model this order is absent (data type - the set).

Therefore, the idea of ​​adapting TW to create books looks promising for both potential authors and in terms of expanding the application of the TW platform.

Discussion

The project extends a discussion taking place at the TW forum under topic Autonumbering.

Idea of the project

3rd January 2019 at 12:18pm
Autonum project

The whole idea of the project is to equip TW with tools for auto indexing of various types of internal objects in the text with successive referencing to them.

Very roughly the overall procedure comprises the following steps:

  1. Generating the TOC index
  2. Generating the object type indexes
  3. Internal text object in wiki text
  4. Storing the object type indexes
  5. Object manipulation

Generating the TOC index

2nd January 2019 at 12:08pm
Idea of the project

Generating an index of single articles (tiddlers) included into a book (or whatever this type of publication is called). This index hereafter is called TOC index.

The simplest and sufficient form of this index would be a list of tiddler titles in a predefined order. The order could be predefined in many ways by:

  • the StoryRiver list (the order of tiddlers can be managed by dragging-and-dropping under tab Open of the Sidebar),
  • the DefaultTiddlers list (can be set up at ControlPanel / Info / Basics),
  • a macro procedure similar to the TOC macro,
  • a manually composed list or
  • other means.

Generating the object type indexes

2nd January 2019 at 12:07pm
Idea of the project

Collecting the first occurrence and incremental numbering of every internal text object according to the order of articles (tiddlers) determined by the TOC index.

Such a numbering is done independently for each type of internal text objects. Altough the set of internal text object types can be determined dynamically, it would be worthwhile to assign the following types of internal text objects preliminary:

  • TBL - tables
  • FRM - formulas
  • REF - bibliographical references
  • IMG - images or graphs
  • NOT - notes or footnotes
  • DEF - definitions including abbreviations

In result of this collecting and numbering the object type index is created for each object type identified.

Internal text object in wiki text

2nd January 2019 at 1:48pm
Idea of the project

Any internal text type object is stored in a single tiddler. Its content is stored in the text field. The object description is stored in field caption. Field objtype filled in with object type name.

For example, SVG image as an internal text object may have the following look:

title: BlueBall
type: image/svg+xml
caption: That is a blue ball
objtype: IMG

<svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
     xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"
     width="150" height="100">
  <circle cx="100" cy="50" r="40" stroke="black" stroke-width="2" fill="blue" />
</svg>

Formula as an internal text object may have the following look:

title: Біном Н'ютона
type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki
caption: Newton binomial formula
objtype: FRM

$$
(a+b)^n = \sum_{k= 0}^n C^k_n a^k b^{n-k}
$$

Storing the object type indexes

2nd January 2019 at 12:06pm
Idea of the project

Each object type index is stored into a corresponding shadow tiddler. Its title is formed from two parts:

  • prefix, for instance, $:/boa/autonum/ and
  • object type name, for instance, IMG for images

The tiddler itself is of the DataTiddler type, namely, DictionaryTiddlers. Each index record in this tiddler is formed by:

  • a particular internal text object title followed with colon without space,
  • internal text object index.

As an example index tiddler for bibligraphical references may have the following look:

title: $:/boa/autonum/REF
type: application/x-tiddler-dictionary

MAX_OBJ_COUNT: 4
JS-1492: 1
WS-2016: 2
SJ-2015: 3
SJ-2017: 4

MAX_OBJ_COUNT is a special term reserved for storing the total number of objects of a given type. Thus this term cannot be used for object naming.

Object manipulation

3rd January 2019 at 10:17am
Idea of the project

The initial procedure of generating the object type indexes is made by collecting the first occurrence of the following macro expression over all the TW text (see Generating the object type indexes):

<<autonumdisp tid:obj_title ns:obj_type>>

where

  • obj_title - a particular object title, which is the value of parameter tid (contractation of tiddler). In case obj_title contains spaces it has to be folded in qoutes;
  • obj_type - a type of this text object (i.e. FRM, IMG, etc.), which the value of parameter ns (contractation of name space);
  • any of tokens tid: or ns: in the macro call expression autonumdisp can be omitted, however, preserving the order of arguments: first - tid, second - ns. Finally if argument ns is omitted, then its default value is REF.

Putting macro autonumdisp in wiki text pursues two goals:

  1. initiates the index number for the given object type (name space) according to location of the macro call in the TOC index and inside the tiddler itself;
  2. usually reveals the complete object depending on the object type.

After the the object type indexes have been generated and stored three other macros can be used:

  • for referencing the object by its number in a corresponding object type index
    <<autonumref tid:obj_title ns:obj_type>>
  • for revealing a complete numbered list of descriptions of objects of a given type (name space)
    <<autonumlist ns:obj_type>>
  • for revealing the number (maximal index) of objects of a given type (name space)
    <<autonum ns:obj_type>>

Code re-writing

3rd January 2019 at 12:17pm
Further development

The code for generating the object type indexes has to be re-worked and re-written from Octave to JS for Node.js and TW. As a good starting pattern for this an elegant JS plugin titled autoref.js by author Mark S. can be considered.

It would be great if somebody from the TW community would complete the development of this code based on the mentioned and other working-outs:

  • This Autonum project by Olegh Bondarenko;
  • autoref.js by Mark S.;
  • Footnotes and Textstretch - not sure who are authors;
  • PopupFootnotes by Danielo Rodriguez;
  • Numbers - Titles and Footnotes Test by Thomas Elmiger.

Alternative TOC

3rd January 2019 at 12:16pm
Further development

The current "classical" TOC macros seems a bit awkward for building the TOC index (see Generating the TOC index). Instead, the drag-and-drop mechanism recently extended for lists (see list-links-draggable macro) looks much more suitable for hierarchical TOC interactive building and therefore could be used for TOC index building with much more ease.

It would be great if somebody from the TW community would challenge the development of this alternative TOC tool.

Code for generating the object type indexes

2nd January 2019 at 8:50pm
Code used

The main idea is to build the object type indexes for TW under Node.js at a folder where all the TW tiddler files (*.tid) are located in a local computer.

Because of my illiteracy in JS programming I decided to develop the code using Octave (free Matlab clone).

The code contains the main following parts:

  1. autonum.m
  2. build_toc_index.m
  3. collect_single_tid_anchors.m
  4. init_anchor_struct.m
  5. store_obj_inds.m

Of course it would be a good solution to re-write this code using JS for embedding it into TW.

autonum.m

2nd January 2019 at 8:27pm
Code for generating the object type indexes 
function autonum
  clear all
  # Global structutes
  global DATA SEQ_NUM ANCHORS;
  # Global constants
  global NS_LIST MAX_OBJ_COUNT_FLD AUTONUM_TW_FOLDER;
  NS_LIST = {'REF' 'IMG' 'FRM' 'TBL' 'NOT' 'ABB'};
  MAX_OBJ_COUNT_FLD = 'MAX_OBJ_COUNT';
  AUTONUM_TW_FOLDER = '$:/boa/autonum/';
  # Non-global constants
  tid_folder = 'D:\boa_protw\_AUTONUM\tw5node\tiddlers\';
  root_toc_title = "My book";
  
  ### Init ANCHORS structure
  init_anchor_struct;
  ### Build TOC index for the whole TW
  toc_index = build_toc_index(tid_folder, root_toc_title);
  ### Build AUTONUM index for each object type for the whole TW
  for i=toc_index
    printf('%i [%i] (%s) %s\n', ...
    DATA(i).heading_level, DATA(i).seq_num, ...
    DATA(i).headingorder, DATA(i).title);
    collect_single_tid_anchors(tid_folder, DATA(i).title);
  endfor
  ### Storing the result in corresponding DATATIDDLERS
  store_obj_inds(tid_folder);
endfunction

build_toc_index.m

2nd January 2019 at 8:27pm
Code for generating the object type indexes 
function toc_index = build_toc_index(tid_folder, root_toc_title)
  global DATA;
  
  get_tid_data(tid_folder);
  ind = init_build_toc(root_toc_title);
  build_toc(DATA(ind).title, DATA(ind).heading_level);

  a = {DATA.seq_num};
  for i = 1:length(a)
    ix(i) = !isempty(a{i});
  endfor
  toc_index = find(ix);
  [~, inds] = sort([DATA(toc_index).seq_num]);
  toc_index = toc_index(inds);
endfunction

function build_toc(title, heading_level)
  global DATA SEQ_NUM;
  ind = get_title_index(title);
  ix = [];
  for i = 1:length(DATA)
    ind = find(strcmp(DATA(i).tags, title));
    if (!isempty(ind) && !isempty(DATA(i).headingorder))
      ix = [ix i];
    endif
  endfor
  if (isempty(ix))
    return
  endif
  s_headingorder = [];
  for i = 1:length(ix)
    s_headingorder = [s_headingorder; 1*DATA(ix(i)).headingorder];
  endfor
  [~, ixs] = sortrows(s_headingorder,[1 2 3]);
  ++heading_level;
  for i = 1:length(ix)
    j = ix(ixs(i));
    DATA(j).heading_level = heading_level;
    DATA(j).seq_num = ++SEQ_NUM;
    build_toc(DATA(j).title, heading_level);
  endfor
endfunction

function ind = init_build_toc(root_toc_title)
  global DATA SEQ_NUM;
  ind = get_title_index(root_toc_title);
  DATA(ind).heading_level = 1;
  SEQ_NUM = 1;
  DATA(ind).seq_num = SEQ_NUM;
endfunction

function get_tid_data(tid_folder)
  global DATA;
  f = dir([tid_folder '*.tid']);
  for i = 1:length(f)
    fid = fopen([f(i).folder '\' f(i).name], 'r');
    txt = fread(fid,inf,'uchar')';
    fclose(fid);
    [s, e] = regexp(char(txt), '\r*\n\r*\n');
    header = char(txt(1:s(1)));
    t = regexp(header, '^([^:]+):\s([^\n]*)$', 'tokens', 'lineanchors');
    for j = 1:length(t)
      DATA(i).(t{j}{1}) = t{j}{2};
    endfor
    if(isfield(DATA(i),'tags'))
      DATA(i).tags = tags2cell (char(DATA(i).tags));
    endif
  endfor
endfunction

function indx = get_title_index(title)
  global DATA;
  indx = find(strcmp({DATA(:).title}, title));
  return;
endfunction

function tags = tags2cell (x)
  tags1 = regexp(x, '\[\[([^\]]+)\]\]', 'tokens');
  [s,e] = regexp(x, '(\[\[[^\]]+\]\])');
  for i = length(s):-1:1
    x(s(i):e(i)) = [];
  endfor
  tags2 = regexp(x, '([^\s]+)', 'tokens');
  tags = [tags1{:} tags2{:}];
endfunction

collect_single_tid_anchors.m

2nd January 2019 at 8:52pm
Code for generating the object type indexes 
function collect_single_tid_anchors(tid_folder, tid_file)
  global ANCHORS;
  fid = fopen([tid_folder tid_file '.tid'], 'r');
  txt = char(fread(fid,Inf,'uchar'))';
  t = regexp(txt, '<<autonumdisp\s+([^>]+)\s*>>', 'tokens');
  fclose(fid);
  
  for i = 1:length(t)
    s = t{i}{1};
    [pars, s] = get_all_pars(s);
    if (!isfield(ANCHORS.(pars.ns), pars.tid))
      ANCHORS.(pars.ns).(pars.tid) = ++ANCHORS.(pars.ns).MAX_OBJ_COUNT;
    endif
  endfor
endfunction

function [pars, s] = get_all_pars(s)
  global matches;
  matches.tid = '(tid\s*:)';
  matches.ns = '(ns\s*:)';
  matches.flds = '.*(tid|ns).*';
  matches.qtok = '"([^"]+)"';
  matches.nqtok = '([\w\-\.])';
  matches.sp = '\s+';
  matches.sa = '\s*';
  
  pars.tid = [];
  pars.ns  = [];
  [pars, s] = get_par(pars, s, matches.tid);
  [pars, s] = get_par(pars, s, matches.ns);
  if (isempty(pars.tid))
    [pars, s] = get_par_expl(pars, s, 'tid');
  endif
  [pars, s] = get_par_expl(pars, s, 'ns');
  if (isempty(pars.ns))
    pars.ns = 'REF';
  endif
endfunction

function [pars, s] = get_par_expl(pars, s, fld)
  s = strtrim(s);
  if (!isempty(s))
    [tok, s2, e2] = get_left_tok(s);
    pars.(fld) = tok;
    s(s2(1):e2(1)) = [];
  endif
endfunction

function [pars, s] = get_par(pars, s, smatch)
  global matches;
  [s1, e1] = regexp(s, smatch);
  if (isempty(e1))
    return;
  endif
  ss = s(e1(1)+1:end);
  [tok, s2, e2] = get_left_tok(ss);
  fld = regexp(smatch,matches.flds,'tokens');
  fld = fld{1}{1};
  pars.(fld) = tok;
  s(s1(1):e1(1)+e2(1)) = [];
endfunction

function [tok, s2, e2] = get_left_tok(ss)
  global matches;
  if (!length(ss))
    tok = '';
    s2 = [];
    e2 = [];
    return;
  endif
  [tok, se2] = regexp(ss, ['^' matches.sa matches.qtok], ...
                 'tokens', 'tokenExtents');
  d = 1;
  if (isempty(se2))
    [tok, se2] = regexp(ss, ['^' matches.sa matches.nqtok], ...
                   'tokens', 'tokenExtents');
    d = 0;
  endif
  tok = tok{1}{1};
  s2 = se2{1}(1) - d;
  e2 = se2{1}(2) + d;
endfunction

init_anchor_struct.m

2nd January 2019 at 8:54pm

function init_anchor_struct
  global ANCHORS NS_LIST;
  for i = 1:length(NS_LIST)
    ANCHORS.(NS_LIST{i}).MAX_OBJ_COUNT = 0;
  endfor
endfunction

store_obj_inds.m

2nd January 2019 at 10:07pm
Code for generating the object type indexes 
function store_obj_inds(tid_folder)
  global ANCHORS AUTONUM_TW_FOLDER;
  fld_names = fieldnames(ANCHORS);
  for i = 1:length(fld_names)
    ns = fld_names{i};
    obj_struct = ANCHORS.(ns);
    if (obj_struct.MAX_OBJ_COUNT < 1)
      continue;
    endif
    tid_fn = [tid_folder regexprep(AUTONUM_TW_FOLDER, '[:/]', '_') ...
         ns '.tid'];
    tid_header = build_tid_header(ns);
    tid_names = fieldnames(obj_struct);
    fid = fopen(tid_fn,'w');
    for j = 1:length(tid_header)
      fprintf(fid, '%s\n', tid_header{j})
    endfor
    for j = 1:length(tid_names)
      fprintf(fid,'%s: %i\n',tid_names{j}, obj_struct.(tid_names{j}))
    endfor
    fclose(fid);
  endfor
endfunction

function tid_header = build_tid_header(ns)
  global AUTONUM_TW_FOLDER;
  tid_header = {
    'type: application/x-tiddler-dictionary'
    ['title: ' AUTONUM_TW_FOLDER ns sprintf('\n')]
  };
endfunction

Code for object manipulation

2nd January 2019 at 9:02pm
Code used

There are five simple macros here for object manipulation, which are located in $:/boa/macro/autonum:

\define autonumtid(ns:"REF") $:/boa/autonum/$ns$

\define autonumdisp(tid, ns:"REF")
<$reveal type="match" default=$ns$ text="REF">
<$link to="""$tid$""">[<$transclude tiddler=<<autonumtid $ns$>> index="$tid$"/>]</$link>
</$reveal>
<$reveal type="match" default=$ns$ text="IMG">
<div style="text-align:center;">
[img width=80% [$tid$]]<br/>
Figure <$transclude tiddler=<<autonumtid $ns$>> index="$tid$"/>. {{$tid$!!caption}}
</div>
</$reveal>
<$reveal type="match" default=$ns$ text="FRM">
<div style="width:80%;display:inline-block">
{{$tid$}}
</div>
<span style="vertical-align:middle;">
(<$transclude tiddler=<<autonumtid $ns$>> index="$tid$"/>)</span>
</$reveal>
<$reveal type="match" default=$ns$ text="TBL">
<div style="text-align:center;">
Table <$transclude tiddler=<<autonumtid $ns$>> index="$tid$"/>. {{$tid$!!caption}}
</div>
<div style="text-align:center;">

{{$tid$}}
</div>
</$reveal>
\end

\define autonumref(tid, ns:"REF")
<$reveal type="match" default=$ns$ text="REF">
<$link to="""$tid$""">[<$transclude tiddler=<<autonumtid $ns$>> index="$tid$"/>]</$link>
</$reveal>
<$reveal type="match" default=$ns$ text="IMG">
<$link to="""$tid$"""><$transclude tiddler=<<autonumtid $ns$>> index="$tid$"/></$link>
</$reveal>
<$reveal type="match" default=$ns$ text="FRM">
<$link to="""$tid$""">(<$transclude tiddler=<<autonumtid $ns$>> index="$tid$"/>)</$link>
</$reveal>
<$reveal type="match" default=$ns$ text="TBL">
<$link to="""$tid$"""><$transclude tiddler=<<autonumtid $ns$>> index="$tid$"/></$link>
</$reveal>
\end

\define autonumlist(ns:"REF")
<$set name="tidns" value=<<autonumtid $ns$>> >
<$list filter='[<tidns>indexes[]] -[title[MAX_OBJ_COUNT]]' variable='xyz'>
<$transclude tiddler=<<tidns>> index=<<xyz>>/>. <$transclude tiddler=<<xyz>> field="caption"/><br/>
</$list>
<$set>
\end

\define autonummax(ns:"REF")
<$transclude tiddler=<<autonumtid $ns$>> index="MAX_OBJ_COUNT"/>
\end
